Memory Exercise:

On some HPC systems an application will be killed if it exceeds a
virtual memory limit (VIRT memory), and on others only when physical
memory (RES memory) is exceded.

Some programs allocate all their required memory at the beginning,
others do it piecemeal throughout the program. Allocated memory, immediately
appears as Virtual memory (even though it may not be used). Hence, for the 
former (non-piecemeal) a very large virtual memory will initially appear, 
and stay constant; for the latter the virtual memory increases throught the program.  

The resident memory is the "physical memory" used.  It is the part of
the allocated memory that is written to (for the first time) and
now has to exist in real memory.  If the allocated (virtual) is 
always initialized immediately, the the virtual and physical memory
change together.  Any allocated storage that is never initialized 
(used) remains virtual memory.

Optional: Review in memoryc.c or mymoryf.F90 how the memory is allocated 
          and initialize throughout the program.

After executioning a C code and a Fortran code with remora, 
see if the maximum virtual and resident memory are the same 
in the summary, and then evaluate how they changed throughout the run.
(They were written to differ.)

  You will build C and F90 memory allocator executables. (memoryc and memoryf)
  You will "attach" remora and acquire some details about the execution.

